==<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Overview</span>==
{{Blurimage|file=Display.png|caption=An image of a Display. The recording had shown it killing a wanderer. The photographer is deceased.|width=300px}}
'''Entity 25''', most often referred to as the '''Displays''', are bipedal humanoids that resemble a construct of randomized pieces of furniture, hardware, appliances, or other household objects. As of now, it is believed that no two recorded Displays share the same appearance, all containing different arbitrary elements that almost seem to be fused together completely at random. Despite the entities' irregular physiology, instances have been observed moving at speeds estimated at up to 10 miles per hour (16 kilometers per hour). Displays, while standing upright, will vary in height depending on the instance, but typically range from 12 to 20 feet tall (3.6 to 6.1 meters tall). The Displays' origins are unknown as of now, but the leading theory (yet to be confirmed) is that the creature is using a form of hyperrealistic mimicry to imitate ordinary furniture.

Displays are most commonly encountered in levels containing large quantities of furniture, though sightings have been reported in a variety of unrelated environments. These entities have the ability to disassemble themselves at will, making them look identical to an unorganized pile of furniture. This ability makes them blend in with their surroundings so much so that they are indistinguishable from non-anomalous pieces of furniture. In fact, several pieces of recovered footage submitted to the [[M.E.G.]] depict wanderers passing directly by (what is assumed to be) dormant Displays without noticing them. Although no Displays share the same physical form, it is unknown why they all take the same basic humanoid shape, especially since the pieces that make up their body seem to be selected with little regard to practicality or symmetry. On top of this, many can have mutations, such as an extra "arm" or "head," or a limb that is much longer than the other, which seems to have no practical use. 

==<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Behavior</span>==
Due to the rarity of Displays and the low number of Display attack survivors, the nature of the entities is yet to be fully understood, but with the available data that the M.E.G. currently has access to, we have composed many plausible theories. That being said, Displays seem to be ambush predators that use their unassuming appearance as a hunting tactic. The entities spend a lot of time in a dormant state where they, quite literally, fall apart, presenting themselves as an innocent pile of random furniture. When in this state, they seem to be fully aware of their surroundings, being able to get up if they choose to pursue a prey item or switch positions, although, this could just be them sensing prey nearby. Interestingly, Displays only seem to be hostile towards humans (or humanoid entities with similar intelligence), and even then, will refuse to attack certain wanderers who pass by. As mentioned previously, recovered videos found by M.E.G. have shown wanderers walking or even sitting beside a dormant Display, with neither side taking an offensive or defensive reaction. 

A few seconds before a Display begins a pursuit, they will often emit an audible creaking sound, almost as a warning. After the sound is heard, the Display will "wake up," reassemble itself through currently unknown means, and begin chasing its chosen victim. For simplicity's sake, this state will be called active. While Displays can reach a speed faster than the average person can run, their size and bulk probably make traversing through most indoor levels a challenge for them, and even then, we've seen that Displays rarely go full speed, instead opting to go at a more leisurely pace. As to why they do this is still yet to be determined, but the accepted explanation is that going too fast could compromise their bodies. 

Recorded pursuits suggest that the entities are intelligent enough to hinder their prey during chase, whether by throwing objects or tinkering with environmental features. Several recordings from wanderers show that the Displays will also try to steer their victims into dead-ends to make escape impossible, showing that they have the ability to remember and map out nearby areas of the level they inhabit, though recent information suggests this could just be a coincidence. Displays are only known to give up a chase after their victim has either run too far away, or the victim managed to hide well enough. When this happens, they have been noted to go back to the place they laid dormant most of the time.

Of the few recorded instances of Displays that exist, only a handful can be used to accurately describe what Displays do to their victims once they have been caught. Of those few recorded cases, Displays have most often killed the victim through either severe blunt-force trauma caused by the entities or by being pinned beneath the entity and crushed under its immense weight. However, one recorded instance depicted the Display in question seizing the wanderer by the leg and dragging them far enough away for their screams not to be audible. The ultimate fate of the wanderer remains unknown, but has been deemed irrelevant. Through this, we can deduce that the entity most likely does not eat (or that's what it did to the wanderer it took away). We currently do not know why Displays hunt and kill wanderers, and information is greatly appreciated.

==<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Biology</span>==
Displays appear to be composed of nothing besides random pieces of furniture, household objects, and other appliances of the sort. They also look like they lack any connective tissue between each part of their body. Despite this, all instances are capable of walking, running, and seemingly are even capable of decision-making, though, through what biological features remains unknown. Many Displays possess structures that should be incapable of holding their weight or balance, including uneven limbs, narrow and unsteady bases, and unattached segments. While many theories have been proposed on how Displays are able to maintain their structural stability, none have been tested at this time. 

The process by which Displays are able to disassemble and reassemble themselves at will remains a subject of ongoing investigation. As mentioned before, when Displays are exhibiting dormancy, they split themselves into a pile of individual pieces before remaining motionless for extended periods of time. Upon initiating a pursuit, all of the pieces individually "float" back into position to reform the humanoid shape without any visible means of moving on their own. Possible explanations could include electromagnetic force, invisible connective tissues, or some kind of illusion, but none of these have been proven. After reforming, the pieces are mostly stationary, but can be knocked off of the full creature with a considerable amount of force, shown to us by a recording of a wanderer attempting to fight one with a large metal rod, and they successfully knocked the creature's head off before the Display ended up taking the wanderer's life. 

Perhaps the most perplexing aspect of Displays is their lack of any typical biological structures. They do not seem to have any room for bones, muscles, blood, sensory organs, or even any kind of nervous system. Nevertheless, Displays seem to have abilities that come with most of these missing structures, such as sight, hearing, coordinated movement, and even memory of the Backrooms' floor plans at the very least. As a result, M.E.G. continues to classify Entity 25 as a living being, though the criteria used to justify this classification remain under review. Further study is required as of now. 
==<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Documentation</span>==
<div style="background:black; color:white;font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; padding:10px;border:2px white double; border-radius:30px; padding:20px;"><center>I didn't know what I was looking at when I saw it. Hell, I still don't know, it was beyond me, but let me tell you that you should have seen it. You'd be surprised it could stand up on its own and that it wasn't crawling on the ground like a little baby going, "Wah! Wah! Wah!" <br>
<br>
Yeah, I know... look it was terrifying. As soon as it took its first step at me, I said, "nope," and ran out of there as fast as my legs could go. I was stuck in a dead end so I locked the door behind me and prayed to God that it couldn't get through. Lo and behold, it broke the door off its hinges the second time it rammed it. When it rammed it the first time I already went to hide in the closet that was conveniently in there, because despite all my bad luck, I managed to get pretty lucky with that.<br>
Well, after the door broke, it took two more rams for it to get through the sides of the doorway, and I'm over here pissing myself in the closet like, "please don't check in here," and thankfully it didn't. I get to live another day...{{Underline|FFFFFF}}An interview with the only willing survivor, Garrett Jackson.
</center></div>
==<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Do's and Don'ts with Displays</span>==


===<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Do's</span>===

* Be wary of piles of furniture.
* Run as fast as possible if seen active.
* Turn the other way if you hear sounds comparable to collapsing furniture from afar.
* Hide if no other options present themselves.

===<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Dont's</span>===

* Go towards suspicious sounds.
* Try to fight it.
